Environmental fate Ecotoxicity Human health &nbsp Ecotoxicity Low alert: Bees acute oral ecotoxicity: Low; Earthworms chronic ecotoxicity: Low Warning: Significant data are missing Human health Low alert GENERAL INFORMATION Description A naturally occuring fungal parasite used to control pests during post-harvest storage Example pests controlled Various Coleoptera beetles; Sawtoothed grain beetle ( Oryzaephilus surinamensis ), Wheat weevil ( Sitophilus granarius ); Lined flat bark beetle ( Cryptolestes ferrugineus ) Example applications Grain stores; Storage areas Efficacy & activity - Appearance and life cycle Beauveria bassiana has filamentous fungal spores. On insects, the fungal growth appears as a dense, white powder. Fungus populates via vegetative growth in the host haemocoel Substance source A ubiquitous organism originally isolated from an infected adult coleopteran Sitophilus oryzae in a UK grain store. Uses Plant protection Target pests Coleoptera pests Oryzaephilus surinamensis, Sitophilus granarius & Cryptolestes ferrugineus Target host Grain stores; Storage areas Farming system suitability - CAS RN - EC number - CIPAC number - US EPA chemical code - PubChem CID - Molecular mass - Chemical name Beauveria bassiana strain IMI389521 PIN (Preferred Identification Name) - IUPAC name - CAS name - Forever chemical - Other status information - Relevant Environmental Water Quality Standards - Herbicide Resistance Class (HRAC MoA class) Not applicable Herbicide Resistance Class (WSSA MoA class) Not applicable Insecticide Resistance Class (IRAC MoA class) UNF Fungicide Resistance Class (FRAC MOA class) Not applicable Examples of recorded resistance - Physical state Fungus Commercial Property Value Availability status Current Introduction & key dates 1979, first described Example manufacturers & suppliers of products using this active now or historically - Example products using this active Bb38 Formulation and application details Usually supplied as a dustable powder Commercial production Beauveria bassiana is commercially produced through a controlled fermentation process that ensures high spore viability and purity. The production begins with the selection of a genetically stable and virulent strain, which is cultured in nutrient-rich liquid media under sterile conditions. Once optimal fungal growth is achieved, the culture is transferred to solid substrates, such as rice or other grains, for mass sporulation. After sufficient incubation, the spores are harvested, dried (often via freeze-drying or spray-drying), and formulated into various products. Impact on climate of production and use As microbial-based biopesticide production processes tend to use fermentation-based production rather than chemical synthesis, have a lower fossil fuel input in formulation and active ingredient creation, and have reduced downstream emissions due to biodegradability and minimal soil disruption, the life-cycle GHG emissions are expected to be low. Whilst hard and precise data are not available, broad estimates suggest that typically emissions are likely to be below 5 kg CO₂e/kg. These chiral centres allow the molecule to exist in multiple stereoisomeric forms, including enantiomers and diastereomers. However, only the specific (2S,2S,2S)-isomer is biologically active. Introduction & key dates 1984, registered Japan Example manufacturers & suppliers of products using this active now or historically Bayer CropScience Meiji Seika Kaisha Japan Example products using this active Basta Ignite Liberty Herbie Formulation and application details Usually supplied as a soluble powder or as liquid formulations Commercial production It is produced commercially through a fermentation process involving specific Streptomyces strains of soil bacteria. The selected bacterial strains are cultured in a controlled environment to produce bilanafos. It is then extracted from the fermentation broth and purified. The purified bilanafos is chemically converted into bilanafos-sodium and formulated. Impact on climate of production and use Data for the amount of life cycle GHGs produced by bilanafos are not available in the public domain. However, whilst estimates vary, more general data suggests that between 18 and 27 kilograms of CO₂e is emitted per kilogram of herbicide produced. The process begins with the fermentation of a specific strain of the bacterium Streptomyces avermitilis , which produces avermectin B1b as a secondary metabolite. Gibberellic acid BPDB: Biopesticides DataBase Top Environmental Fate Ecotoxicology Human Health Translations Home A to Z: All Micro-organism related Macro-organism related Plant-derived Animal-derived Other naturals Search Support Edit history Purchasing and licensing Industry collaboration N E W - New support docs available - Newsletter Aug 2025 - User survey Gibberellic acid Last updated: 27/08/2025 (Also known as: gibberellic acid; Gibberellin A3) Hazard alerts The following alerts are based on the data in the tables below. An absence of an alert does not imply the substance has no implications for human health, biodiversity or the environment but just that we do not have the data to form a judgement. These hazard alerts do not take account of usage patterns or exposure, thus do not represent risk. Environmental fate Ecotoxicity Human health Environmental fate High alert: Drainflow: Very mobile Ecotoxicity Moderate alert: Birds chronic ecotoxicity: Moderate; Daphnia acute ecotoxicity: Moderate; Bees acute contact ecotoxicity: Moderate Human health Moderate alert: Genotoxic; Reproduction/development effects GENERAL INFORMATION Description A plant growth regulator with a variety of uses including improving fruit set, increasing berry size and controlling fruit maturity Example pests controlled Growth; Yield; Stress Example applications Top fruit; Soft fruit including grapes; Hops Efficacy & activity Gibberellic acid has been proven as a biostimulant by both extensive lab and field studies over the last century. In a study with rice, gibberellic acid treatment was shown to significantly increased plant height, earlier flowering, and higher seed yield. Application to grapevines has been found to enhance berry size and improve cluster compactness. This leads to higher market value and better quality produce. Gibberellic treatment to wheat has been shown to increase stem elongation, leading to taller plants with more biomass. With tomatoes, gibberellic acid has been shown to promote early flowering and fruit set, leading to an extended harvest period and increased total yield. It contains multiple chiral centres, particularly within its fused ring system and side chains, which allow for the existence of optical isomers. Additionally, under certain conditions such as heat or acid exposure, gibberellic acid can undergo structural rearrangements, forming isomers like allo-gibberic acid, which retain the same molecular formula but differ in connectivity and stereochemistry. Yes Cambridge Crystallographic Data Centre diagrams Common Name Relationship Link Gibberllin A3 - General status Biopesticide type Plant Growth Regulator; Other substance Other bioactivity & uses Biostimulant - growth enhancement & improvement of abiotic stress resiliance Substance groups Micro-organism derived substance Minimum active substance purity 850 g kg⁻¹ Known relevant impurities EU 2019 dossier: Fumonisin B1, B2 total = 200 μg kg⁻¹ Substance origin Natural Mode of action Gibberellic acid has various physiological and morphological effects on plants. It promotes stem elongation by stimulating both cell division and elongation. It activates genes that produce enzymes responsible for cell wall loosening, allowing cells to expand. It also helps plants cope with various abiotic stresses, such as salinity and drought, by modulating physiological and biochemical processes. Substance source It is naturally found in various sources including fungi, many plants (e.g. cereal grains like rice, corn, wheat, and barley) amd some bacteria. It is also found in the developing seeds of peaches, onion bulbs, spinach, and ferns. The primary commercial source of gibberellic acid is the fungus Gibberella fujikuroi Uses Crop protection; Yield enhancement Target pests - Target host Top fruit; Soft fruit including grapes; Hops Farming system suitability - CAS RN 77-06-5 EC number 201-001-0 CIPAC number 307 US EPA chemical code 043801 PubChem CID - Molecular mass 346.37 PIN (Preferred Identification Name) - IUPAC name (3S,3aS,4S,4aS,7S,9aR,9bR,12S)-7,12-dihydroxy-3-methyl-6-methylene-2-oxoperhydro-4a,7-methano-9b,3-propenoazuleno[1,2-b]furan-4-carboxylic acid CAS name (1α,2β,4aα,4bβ,10β)-2,4a,7-trihydroxy-1-methyl-8-methylenegibb-3-ene-1,10-dicarboxylic acid 1,4a-lactone Forever chemical - Other status information - Relevant Environmental Water Quality Standards - Herbicide Resistance Class (HRAC MoA class) Not applicable Herbicide Resistance Class (WSSA MoA class) Not applicable Insecticide Resistance Class (IRAC MoA class) Not applicable Fungicide Resistance Class (FRAC MOA class) Not applicable Examples of recorded resistance - Physical state White crystalline solid Related substances & organisms gibberellins potassium gibberellate Commercial Property Value Availability status Current Introduction & key dates 1926, discovered in Japan;  circa 1935, introduced Example manufacturers & suppliers of products using this active now or historically ICI Plant Protection Abbott Nihon Nohyaku BOC Sciences Stoller Australia Pty.Ltd Fine Agrochemicals Ltd Interfarm (UK) Ltd Nufarm Americas Ltd Example products using this active Berelex Activol Grocel Brellin Cekugib GIBB 3 N-Large Gibberellic Acid Growth Regulant ProGibb Novagib GibGro Formulation and application details Available as granules, water-soluble tablets, soluble powders and soluble crystal formulations Commercial production The most common method of commercial production is using a process called Submerged Fermentation. The fungus is cultivated in a liquid nutrient medium where it produces gibberellic acid. Key factors like pH, temperature, and nutrient concentration are carefully controlled to optimize production. Solid-State Fermentation is an alternative method where the fungus is grown on solid materials like agricultural residues. After fermentation, the gibberellic acid is extracted and purified. Impact on climate of production and use Precise data for the GHG emissions for commercially produced gibberellic acid are not available. However, it is typically made via microbial fermentation which tends to be low emission process. Considering substrate production, fermentation and downstream processing and looking at published data for similar processes, GHG emissions are likely to be in the range of 1–3 tonnes CO₂e/tonne gibberellic acid. The most common method is cold-pressing, where the oil is separated from the juice through centrifugation. Advanced extraction techniques such as steam distillation, microwave-assisted extraction, and supercritical fluid extraction are also being explored to improve yield and sustainability, especially by valorising orange peel waste. Impact on climate of production and use Data for specific plant oils is scarce. However, from publicly available data the carbon footprint of plant oils has been estimated at between 1.0 and 4.0 kg CO₂e per kg of oil. This depends on the plant oil content, agricultural practices and processing methods used. Environmental fate Ecotoxicity Human health &nbsp &nbsp Human health Low alert GENERAL INFORMATION Description A biological fungicide used to control various phytopathogenic fungi Example pests controlled Brown and blossom rots ( Monilinia fructigena, Monilinia laxa, Monilinia fructicola ); Soft rots ( Botrytis spp.); Leaf spots and blights ( Alternaria spp.); Post-harvest decay ( Neofabraea alba ) Example applications Fruit including pome fruits, stone fruits, grapevine, tomato, strawberries Efficacy & activity - Appearance and life cycle Saccharomyces cerevisiae is able to form two cell types: haploid and diploid cells. The life cycle of this species comprises two features: Proliferation and transition.
